The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, August 24, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Calcutta, Aug. 23: Rajendra Singh Lodha has challenged the Hindu undivided family claim of the Birla family. Two weeks back, Birlas  in its opposition to Lodhas discharge of caveat petition in the high court  argued that it was a Hindu undivided family, a claim Lodha is challenging in his affidavit. The affidavit said the assets of the Birla family were divided in the 1980s. So the four Birla members, Krishna Kumar, Basant Kumar, Ganga Prasad and Yasovardhan, did not have any rights on the assets of the MP Birla group.																								 Mumbai, Aug. 23: Tata Consultancy Services today announced that it has invited Naresh Chandra, former ambassador of India to the US, to join its board of directors, just two days before it makes its debut on the bourses.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 23: Maruti Udyog has slashed prices of compact car Zen and Wagon-R by up to Rs 9,000 on all models. According to sources, the prices have been reduced with effect from today.																								 Calcutta, Aug. 23: Arun Kumar Bajoria, chairman of the Hooghly Group of Jute Mills, has been appointed chairman of the Indian Jute Mills Association for 2004-05.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 23: The government has chosen Gail (India) Ltd over Reliance Industries in setting up a Rs 2,500-crore gas cracker project in Assam.
